# ✅ ✅ Chunk Splitting Strategies

> Chunk splitting is about deciding **how and when to split code into smaller bundles** for better loading performance.

***

# ✅ ✅ Two Main Strategies

    1. Route-based splitting ✅
    2. Component-based splitting ✅

***

# ✅ 1. Route-Based Splitting ✅ (MOST COMMON)

***

## 🔹 Idea

👉 Split code based on **routes/pages**

    Each route → separate chunk

***

## ✅ Example

```javascript
import { lazy, Suspense } from "react";

const Home = lazy(() => import("./Home"));
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import("./Dashboard"));
const Profile = lazy(() => import("./Profile"));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<p>Loading...</p>}>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<Home />} />
        <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
        <Route path="/profile" element={<Profile />} />
      </Routes>
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

***

## 🔹 What Webpack does

    main.js → shared code
    home.chunk.js
    dashboard.chunk.js ✅
    profile.chunk.js ✅

***

## ✅ Benefits

✔ Smaller initial bundle  
✔ Faster first load (LCP improvement)  
✔ Good caching

***

## ✅ When to use

👉 Large apps with multiple pages:

*   E-commerce
*   Admin dashboards
*   SaaS apps

***

***

# ✅ 2. Component-Based Splitting ✅

***

## 🔹 Idea

👉 Split based on **heavy components inside a page**

    Load only when component is needed

***

## ✅ Example

```javascript
const Chart = lazy(() => import("./Chart"));

function Dashboard() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>

      <Suspense fallback={<p>Loading chart...</p>}>
        <Chart />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}
```

***

## 🔹 Scenario

👉 Chart is large (D3, charts library)

👉 Load only when user reaches it ✅

***

## ✅ Output

    dashboard.chunk.js
    chart.chunk.js ✅ (lazy)

***

## ✅ Benefits

✔ Reduces unused JS  
✔ Improves runtime performance  
✔ Better for heavy UI components

***

## ✅ When to use

👉 Inside pages:

*   charts
*   modals
*   rich editors
*   maps

***

***

# ✅ ✅ Key Differences

| Feature     | Route-Based         | Component-Based           |
| ----------- | ------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Split level | Page                | Individual component      |
| Use case    | Navigation          | Heavy UI parts            |
| Trigger     | Route change        | Component render          |
| Complexity  | Simple ✅            | Moderate                  |
| Performance | Faster initial load | Fine-grained optimization |

***

***

# ✅ ✅ Real-World Example

***

## ✅ E-commerce App

***

### Route-based splitting:

    /home → Home chunk ✅
    /product → Product chunk ✅
    /checkout → Checkout chunk ✅

***

### Component-based splitting inside Product page:

    Product page:
      - Image gallery ✅ lazy loaded
      - Reviews ✅ lazy loaded
      - Recommendations ✅ lazy loaded

***

✅ Result:

    Fast initial load ✅  
    Load heavy features only when needed ✅

***

***

# ✅ ✅ Combined Strategy (BEST PRACTICE ✅)

👉 Modern apps use BOTH:

    Route-based + Component-based ✅

***

## 🔹 Example

    Route splitting:
      Dashboard page

    Component splitting:
      Chart
      Table
      Filters

***

👉 Result:

    Minimal initial JS ✅  
    On-demand loading ✅  
    Best performance ✅

***

# ✅ ✅ Performance Impact

***

## Without splitting ❌

    Bundle = 2MB
    → Slow load ❌

***

## With Route Splitting ✅

    Initial load = 500KB ✅

***

## With Component Splitting ✅

    Initial = 300KB ✅
    Lazy load rest ✅

***

# ✅ ✅ Pitfalls (Important)

***

### ❌ Too many small chunks

    Too many requests → overhead ❌

***

### ❌ Wrong lazy loading

    Lazy loading critical components ❌
    → bad UX

***

### ✅ Solution

    Split only heavy/non-critical parts ✅

***

***

# ✅ ✅ Senior-Level Insight

***

## 🔹 What should NOT be lazy loaded?

❌ Navbar  
❌ Header  
❌ Core UI

***

## 🔹 What SHOULD be lazy loaded?

✅ Charts  
✅ Modals  
✅ Admin panels  
✅ Rarely used features

***

***

# ✅ ✅ One-Line Interview Answer

> “Route-based splitting loads code per page, improving initial load time, while component-based splitting loads heavy components on demand within a page. In real-world apps, both strategies are combined for optimal performance.”

***

# ✅ ✅ Memory Trick

    Route → split pages ✅  
    Component → split features ✅  
    Both → best performance ✅

